Coronavirus guidance is being updated.
Read what you can and cannot do

North Macedonia has put measures in place to limit the spread of coronavirus (COVID-19).
For information on how to return to the UK from North Macedonia, see Return to the UK
On 16 April, the President of North Macedonia declared a State of Emergency for the whole territory of North Macedonia for a period of 30 days.
On 23 March the Government of North Macedonia introduced a curfew, which all citizens, with a few exceptions for key workers, must obey.
Curfew measures
Effective from Thursday 23 April, the curfew will be Monday to Friday 7pm until 5am for all citizens. On weekends, the curfew will be from Saturday 3pm until Monday 5am.
Additional curfew measures continue for those people aged under 18 and over 67. There is a complete ban on movement of people aged under 18 except for 1pm to 7pm on Monday to Friday. For people aged above 67 years of age, there will be a complete ban from Monday to Friday apart from 5amuntil 12pm. On Saturday, people over the age of 67 are allowed to go out from 5am to 11am, while people aged under 18 years old will be allowed to go out from 12 pm until 3pm.
The Government of North Macedonia has announced that there will be a change in curfew hours over the upcoming May 1 public holiday weekend. From Friday 1 May to Sunday 3 May, people aged between 18 and 67 years old may leave their homes between 5am and 2pm each day; people over 67 years of age may only leave their homes between 5am and 11am and people under 18 years old will be able to go out between 12 noon and 2pm.
The general curfew does not apply to members of law enforcement bodies, army members, firefighters and people in need of emergency medical assistance, or those in a life-threatening condition and people undergoing dialysis treatments. Public transportation will not be available during this time. Availability of taxis will be limited and taxi drivers will be allowed to transport people only to a healthcare facility or a pharmacy.
Local measures
From 23 April, everyone is required to wear protective face coverings when visiting indoor public spaces, such as markets, post offices, health institutions, shops, banks, including when using public transport. Protective face coverings are also required outside in situations when it is not possible to maintain a safe distance from others such as in green markets and open areas that do not allow for two-meters of physical distance between individuals.
This is not obligatory for people staying in their own gardens or balconies, riding a bike, doing open-air sports, or in a passenger vehicle along with the people living in the same household.
The Government of North Macedonia recommends those living at the territory of Kumanovo, Prilep and Tetovo, reduce outings from their homes, as well as designate one family member in charge of buying groceries and medicines.
Organised transport of passengers by bus or van are banned from entering or exiting from Kumanovo and Tetovo municipality.
In the whole of the territory of North Macedonia, restaurants, caf√©s, bars and shopping malls are closed to the public, but grocery stores are permitted to open. Some supermarkets and restaurants are operating via online/telephone orders. Limits are placed on the number of people entering shopping facilities at any time.
Other measures include cancellation of cultural and sporting events; closure of parks; and closure of schools and universities.
Citizens are not allowed to move in public places in groups of more than two people, with the exception of children under the age of 14, if they are accompanied by a parent in the group of two
Entry and borders
Anyone entering North Macedonia from COVID-19 affected areas, regardless of nationality or residency status, are subject to mandatory 14-day quarantine at a state organised quarantine centre, and should follow the standard procedure if symptoms occur.
Effective from Monday 13 April, anyone, returning to North Macedonia from a high-risk country, which currently includes the UK, will have to go into quarantine at a state organised quarantine centre for 21 days instead of 14 days.
The British Embassy Skopje is issuing regular updates on Facebook and Twitter with the latest available information.
Visas
British passport holders do not need a visa to travel to North Macedonia for up to 3 months.
On 23 March, the Government of North Macedonia published on its website additional information on visas for foreigners staying in North Macedonia during the State of Emergency.
Foreigners who are staying in North Macedonia for a short period (with or without a visa), may stay in the territory of North Macedonia, even after the expiry of a visa, for the duration of the State of Emergency. The validity of a temporary residence permit and a permanent residency permit whose period of validity has expired is extended during the duration of the State of Emergency.
Further information
The Ministry of Health also advises if you are a British National in North Macedonia and develop any symptoms of coronavirus, please call +389 78 387 194 or +389 2 15 123.
Further information can be found on the Government of North Macedonia website, which is publishing information and key announcements in English.
See the TravelHealthPro website for further advice on travel abroad and reducing spread of respiratory viruses during the COVID-19 pandemic.
